Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

Problem Statement: E-news Express, an online news portal, would like to expand its business by acquiring new subscribers. The executives at E-news believe that there has been a decline in new monthly subscribers compared to last year. They believe that the main reason for the decline is that the current website is not designed well enough to keep customer's engaged.

Objective:

The design team of the company has created a new landing page in order to keep customers more engaged which will hopefully encourge them to subscribe. In order to test the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers, the Data Science team conducted an experiment by randomly selecting 100 users and dividing them equally into two groups. The existing landing page was served to the first group(control group) and the new landing page to the second group(treatment group). We have been asked to explore the data and perfom a statistical analysis(signifcance level of 5%) to determine the effectivness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers for the news portal by answering the following questions:

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than on the existing landing page?

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page 
greater than the conversion rate for the old page?

3. Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?

4. is the time spent on the new page the same for the different language users?

Determine if users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

In [158]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
sns.boxplot(data=df,x='landing_page',y='time_spent_on_the_page')
plt.show()
In [159]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
sns.boxplot(data=df,x='time_spent_on_the_page',y='landing_page')
plt.show()

The means of the time spent on the old and new landing pages appear to differ.
Users appear to spend more time on the new landing page.

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Ho: μ1=μ2. Users time spent on the new landing page is equal to the time spent on the old landing page. #null hypothesis

Ha: μ1>μ2. Users time spent on the new landing page is greater than time spent on the old landing page. #alternative hypothesis

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

2 sample means independent t-test

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

We will use a significance level of α = 0.05.

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [160]:
new_time_on_page = df[df['landing_page'] =='new']['time_spent_on_the_page']

old_time_on_page = df[df['landing_page'] =='old']['time_spent_on_the_page']
In [161]:
print('The standard deviation of time spent on the new page is:', round(new_time_on_page.std(),2))
print('The standard deviation of time spent on the old page is:', round(old_time_on_page.std(),2))

The standard deviation of time spent on the new page is: 1.82
The standard deviation of time spent on the old page is: 2.58

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [162]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind 


test_stat, p_value =ttest_ind(new_time_on_page, old_time_on_page, equal_var=False, alternative ='two-sided')

print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.0002784762450333098

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [163]:
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')      

As the p-value 0.0002784762450333098 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

At 5% significance level, we reject the null hypothesis. We have enough statistical evidence to say that users spend more time on the new landing page than they do on the old landing page.

A similar approach can be followed to answer the other questions.

In [168]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Ho: p1<=p2. The new page conversion rate is less than or equal to the old page conversion rate.

Ha: p1>p2. The new page conversion rate is greater than the old page conversion rate.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Two Proportion Z-test

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

We will use a significance level of α = 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [169]:
new_page_converted = df[df['group']=='treatment'].converted.value_counts()['yes']

old_page_converted = df[df['group']=='control'].converted.value_counts()['yes']

print('The number of treatment and control users converted to the new page are {0} and {1} respectively'.format(new_page_converted, old_page_converted))

#number of people n the treatment group
n_treatment= df.group.value_counts()['treatment']

#number of people in the control group
n_control=df.group.value_counts()['control']


print('The total number of people who visited the old and new page are {0} and {1} respectively'.format(n_control, n_treatment))

The number of treatment and control users converted to the new page are 33 and 21 respectively
The total number of people who visited the old and new page are 50 and 50 respectively

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [170]:
stat, pval =proportions_ztest([new_page_converted, old_page_converted], [n_control, n_treatment], alternative='two-sided')

print('The p-value is '+str(pval))

The p-value is 0.016052616408112556

Step 6: Compare the p-value with 𝛼¶

In [171]:
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {pval} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {pval} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')  

As the p-value 0.016052616408112556 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

Since the p-value is less than the level of significance(5%), we reject the null hypothesis. Hence we have enough statistical evidence to say that the conversion rate of users visiting the new page is greater than the conversion rate of users visiting the old page.

In [174]:
#import necessary libraries
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Ho: The conversion rate is independent of preferred language.

Ha: The conversion rate is NOT independent of preferred language.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

Chi Square Test of Independence

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

We will use a significance level of α = 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [175]:
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df['language_preferred'], df['converted'])
contingency_table
Out[175]:
converted no yes
language_preferred
English 11 21
French 19 15
Spanish 16 18

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [176]:
#code to calculate p-value
chi2, pvalue1, dof, exp_freq = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
print('The p-value is', pvalue1)

The p-value is 0.2129888748754345

Step 6: Compare the p-value with 𝛼¶

In [177]:
if pvalue1 < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {pvalue1} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {pvalue1} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')  

As the p-value 0.2129888748754345 is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

Since the p-value is greater than the level of significance(5%), we do not reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we do not have enough statistical evidence to say that the conversion rate is NOT independent of preferred language.

The distribution of the time spent on the page appears to be similar for all languages.

English appears to have the highest average time spent on the page(6.66 minutes). French(6.19 minutes), and Spanish(5.84 minutes).

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

Ho: The time spent on the new page is the same for all the different language users.

Ha: At least one of the languages calculated time spent on the new page is not the same from the other different language users.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

One-way ANOVA test

In [183]:
#Shapiro-Wilk's Test
from scipy import stats

print('The p-value is', p_value2)

The p-value is 0.5643684267997742

Since the p-value of the test is very large, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the response follows the normal distribution.

In [184]:
#Levene's Test
from scipy.stats import levene
statistic, p_value2 = levene(df[df['language_preferred']=='English']['time_spent_on_the_page'],
                            df[df['language_preferred']=='French']['time_spent_on_the_page'],
                            df[df['language_preferred']=='Spanish']['time_spent_on_the_page'])
print('The p-value is', p_value2)

The p-value is 0.06515086840327314

Since the p-value is greater than the significance level of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis fo homogeneity of variances.

The populations are normally distributed. The population variances are equal.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

We will use a significance level of α = 0.05

As the p-value 0.8665610536012648 is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

Since the p-value is greater than the level of significance(5%), we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we do not have enough evidence to say that time spent on the new page is any different based on the preferred language of the user.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

Conclusion:

The new landing page is effective at converting more users to subscribers.

Average time spent on the new page has increased for all languages from time spent on the old page.

Users who's preferred language is English had the highest conversion to a subscriber of the new portal. Users who's preferred language is French had the least conversions to a subscriber of the new portal.

We do not have enough evidence to say that time spent on the new page is any different based on the preferred language of the user.

We do not have enough statistical evidence to say that the conversion rate is NOT independent of preferred language.

We have enough statistical evidence to say that the conversion rate of users visiting the new page is greater than the conversion rate of users visiting the old page.

We have enough statistical evidence to say that users spend more time on the new landing page than they do on the old landing page.

Business Recommendations:

The company should continue to use the new landing page since the evidence supports that it is effective at increasing the amount of time spent on the landing page resulting in more users subscribing to the portal.

Since users with preferred language of English had the highest conversion rate, the company should focus on that group to increase subscribers. In addition, more research is needed to determine how to increase subscribers who's preferred language is Spanish or French.
